[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:backend-for-frontend/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:backend-for-frontend/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Modularity is a specific application of concerns to system components (separation by size).
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] In modular systems, each module encapsulates a single concern, and modules are designed, implemented, and understood in isolation before being composed into a larger system.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] While modularity is the most common and recognizable embodiment of SoC in code structure, the principle of Separation of concerns is broader.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] For example, separating requirements analysis from implementation in a project timeline, or separating functional from non-functional requirements in a specification, are valid forms of separation of concerns that do not necessarily require a modular design.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper *"On the Role of Scientific Thought"*, coined the term *separation of concerns* in relation to software qualities such as *correctness* and *efficiency*.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Carlo Ghezzi in his book "Fundamentals of software engineering" promotes Separation Of Concerns as the primary way to tackle the inherited complexity in software production.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Philippe Kruchten in his article "Architectural Blueprints—The “4+1” View Model of Software Architecture" used a model composed of five main views to address large architectures, essentially this is a view-based separation of concerns, where each view focus on a different aspect of the architecture.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Laplante, Phillip also mentioned that separation of concerns can be applied in software design, coding, time, and software qualities.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] The term *separation of concerns* was probably coined by Edsger W.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper "On the role of scientific thought".
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Fifteen years later, it was evident the term *separation of concerns* was becoming an accepted idea.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] SoC is crucial to the design of the Internet.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] In the Internet protocol suite, great efforts have been made to separate concerns into well-defined layers.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] This allows protocol designers to focus on the concerns in one layer, and ignore the other layers.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] The Application Layer protocol SMTP, for example, is concerned about all the details of conducting an email session over a reliable transport service (usually TCP), but not in the least concerned about how the transport service makes that service reliable.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Similarly, TCP is not concerned about the routing of data packets, which is handled at the Internet layer.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are complementary languages used in the development of web pages and websites.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] HTML is mainly used for organization of webpage content, CSS is used for definition of content presentation style, and JavaScript defines how the content interacts and behaves with the user.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Historically, this was not the case: prior to the introduction of CSS, HTML performed both duties of defining semantics and style.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Subject-oriented programming allows separate concerns to be addressed as separate software constructs, each on an equal footing with the others.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Each concern provides its own class-structure into which the objects in common are organized, and contributes state and methods to the composite result where they cut across one another.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Correspondence rules describe how the classes and methods in the various concerns are related to each other at points where they interact, allowing composite behavior for a method to be derived from several concerns.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Multi-dimensional SoC allows the analysis and composition of concerns to be manipulated as a multi-dimensional "matrix" in which each concern provides a dimension in which different points of choice are enumerated, with the cells of the matrix occupied by the appropriate software artifacts.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Aspect-oriented programming allows cross-cutting concerns to be addressed as primary concerns.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] For example, most programs require some form of security and logging.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Security and logging are often secondary concerns, whereas the primary concern is often on accomplishing business goals.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] However, when designing a program, its security must be built into the design from the beginning instead of being treated as a secondary concern.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] Applying security afterwards often results in an insufficient security model that leaves too many gaps for future attacks.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] This may be solved with aspect-oriented programming.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] For example, an aspect may be written to enforce that calls to a certain API are always logged, or that errors are always logged when an exception is thrown, regardless of whether the program's procedural code handles the exception or propagates it.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] In cognitive science and artificial intelligence, it is common to refer to David Marr's levels of analysis.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] At any given time, a researcher may be focusing on what some aspect of intelligence needs to compute, what algorithm it employs, or how that algorithm is implemented in hardware.
[src:backend-for-frontend/separation-of-concerns] This separation of concerns is similar to the interface/implementation distinction in software and hardware engineering.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] documents within a given set of services.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] The relationship between services is minimized to the level that they are only aware of their existence.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be called from anywhere within the network that it is located no matter where it is present.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Services should be designed to be long lived.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Where possible, services should avoid forcing consumers to change if they do not require new features; if you call a service today, you should be able to call the same service tomorrow.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] The services act as black boxes, that is their inner logic is hidden from the consumers.
[src:backend-for-frontend/service-oriented-architecture] Services are independent and control the functionality they encapsulate, from a Design-time and a run-time perspective.
